<Layout title="Burgundy Wine Region" description="A comprehensive guide to Burgundy — the world's most revered wine region, home to the finest Pinot Noir and Chardonnay on Earth.">
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 py-20">
    <p class="text-amber-600 font-medium tracking-wider uppercase text-sm mb-3">Wine Regions</p>
    <h1 class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-stone-900 mb-6">Burgundy: The Soul of Pinot Noir</h1>
    <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm mb-8">By Roberto Carli, CMS · 14 min read</p>

    <div class="prose prose-stone max-w-none">
      <p class="text-lg text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">No wine region on Earth inspires more reverence — or more frustration — than Burgundy. Its wines can be transcendent, ethereal, unlike anything else in the glass. They can also be maddeningly expensive, inconsistent, and nearly impossible to source. Understanding Burgundy is a lifetime project, but here's where to start.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Why Burgundy Matters</h2>
      <p>Burgundy is the birthplace of the concept of <em>terroir</em> — the idea that a wine's character is fundamentally shaped by where the grapes are grown. Centuries of Cistercian monks mapped Burgundy's vineyards plot by plot, identifying which slopes, soils, and exposures produced the finest wines. This meticulous classification system — refined over nearly a thousand years — remains the foundation of Burgundy's appellation structure today.</p>
      <p>The region is also where Pinot Noir and Chardonnay reach their most nuanced expression. Burgundy's cool continental climate pushes these grapes to their limits, producing wines of extraordinary complexity at relatively modest alcohol levels.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">The Classification System</h2>
      <p>Burgundy's quality hierarchy is the most granular in the wine world:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Grand Cru</strong> (1–2% of production) — The 33 greatest vineyards, labeled by vineyard name alone (e.g., "Chambertin," "Montrachet"). These wines command the highest prices and can age for decades.</li>
        <li><strong>Premier Cru (1er Cru)</strong> (~10% of production) — Excellent vineyards named on the label alongside the village (e.g., "Gevrey-Chambertin 1er Cru Clos Saint-Jacques"). Outstanding quality at (relatively) more accessible prices.</li>
        <li><strong>Village</strong> (~35% of production) — Wines from a specific village (e.g., "Meursault," "Volnay"). Quality varies by producer but can be excellent.</li>
        <li><strong>Regional</strong> (~50% of production) — Broad appellations like "Bourgogne Rouge" or "Bourgogne Blanc." Entry-level Burgundy, often blended from vineyards across the region.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Key Sub-Regions</h2>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Chablis</h3>
      <p>Isolated in the north, far from the main Côte d'Or, Chablis produces some of the purest expressions of Chardonnay anywhere. The wines are lean, mineral, and electric with acidity — a world apart from oaky California Chardonnay. Kimmeridgian limestone (ancient seabed) gives Chablis its signature flinty, oyster-shell character.</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Côte de Nuits</h3>
      <p>The northern half of the Côte d'Or and the epicenter of red Burgundy. This narrow strip of east-facing slopes produces the world's most celebrated Pinot Noir. Key villages: Gevrey-Chambertin (powerful, structured), Chambolle-Musigny (elegant, perfumed), Vosne-Romanée (rich, complex — home to the legendary Romanée-Conti), and Nuits-Saint-Georges (earthy, firm).</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Côte de Beaune</h3>
      <p>The southern half of the Côte d'Or, celebrated for white Burgundy. Meursault (round, nutty, rich), Puligny-Montrachet (taut, mineral, precise), and Chassagne-Montrachet (structured, complex) produce Chardonnay of astonishing depth. Red wines from Volnay (silky) and Pommard (robust) are also exceptional.</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Côte Chalonnaise & Mâconnais</h3>
      <p>South of the Côte d'Or, these regions offer genuine Burgundy character at a fraction of the price. Mercurey and Givry (Côte Chalonnaise) produce solid red Burgundy. Pouilly-Fuissé and Saint-Véran (Mâconnais) deliver approachable, often excellent Chardonnay.</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Beaujolais</h3>
      <p>Technically part of the greater Burgundy region, Beaujolais is made from Gamay (not Pinot Noir). The 10 Crus of Beaujolais — Morgon, Fleurie, Moulin-à-Vent, and others — produce some of France's best-value wines: vibrant, food-friendly, and increasingly serious.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Buying Burgundy on a Budget</h2>
      <p>Burgundy's reputation for expense is earned — Grand Cru bottles routinely exceed $200, and top Premier Crus aren't far behind. But smart shopping is possible:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Bourgogne Rouge/Blanc</strong> from top producers (Roulot, Lafon, Dujac) — often $25–$45 and genuinely good</li>
        <li><strong>Côte Chalonnaise</strong> reds and whites — $18–$35 with real Burgundian character</li>
        <li><strong>Cru Beaujolais</strong> — $15–$30 for some of France's best wines, period</li>
        <li><strong>Saint-Véran and Mâcon-Villages</strong> — $15–$25 Chardonnay that over-delivers</li>
        <li><strong>Lesser-known villages:</strong> Marsannay, Santenay, Saint-Romain, and Auxey-Duresses offer village-level quality at a discount because they lack the famous names</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">My Recommendations</h2>
      <p>If you're new to Burgundy, start with a Bourgogne Rouge from Domaine de la Vougeraie or a Marsannay from Bruno Clair. For whites, try a Rully Premier Cru from Dureuil-Janthial or a Mâcon-Vergisson from Guffens-Heynen. These will show you what Burgundy is about without requiring a second mortgage.</p>
